      "description": "FEA-predicted force at 40 mm displacement compared to experimental values across 11 specimens. Mean absolute percent error 7.3%; E/uval = 1.61, satisfying the pre-established acceptance criterion of E/uval < 1.96.",
      "outcome": "Accepted"
    }
  ],
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Ansys Mechanical R2022 R1 commercially validated; FDA in-house solver under documented SQA plan with version control and regression test suite.",
      "rationale": "All three FEA codes (FDA in-house, Ansys Mechanical, DePuy Synthes internal) operate under documented software quality assurance plans. Ansys Mechanical carries commercial V&V documentation. FDA in-house solver is maintained under a formal SQA plan with version-controlled source, automated regression testing, and release notes. Achieves Gradation 2 requirements for medium model risk."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark patch tests and manufactured solution tests completed for linear elastic solid elements; documented in solver verification report.",
      "rationale": "Patch tests and method-of-manufactured-solutions studies confirm correct implementation of the linear elastic constitutive routines and contact formulations used in the pedicle screw model. Results are within machine-precision tolerances for patch tests and within 0.1% for the MMS study at the mesh densities employed."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates QoI change < 2% between medium and fine mesh; Richardson extrapolation GCI < 5%.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh convergence study was conducted on the screw-rod construct model. The grid convergence index (GCI) for construct stiffness is 1.8% and for yield force is 2.4%, both below the 5% threshold. The production mesh (medium density, ~420 000 elements) was selected as the balance between accuracy and computational cost."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals converge to < 1e-6 relative; nonlinear Newton-Raphson residuals < 1e-4 per load step.",
      "rationale": "Sparse direct solver (PARDISO) used for linear steps; Newton-Raphson with line search for nonlinear contact iterations. Force and displacement residuals converge to < 1e-6 relative norm at each increment. No divergence or unconverged increments observed across the 11-specimen ensemble."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model setup peer-reviewed by independent analyst; input deck version-controlled; boundary condition application documented in modeling report.",
      "rationale": "Model setup (geometry import, meshing parameters, material assignment, boundary conditions, contact definitions, and load application) was independently reviewed by a second analyst not involved in model construction. All discrepancies were resolved before simulation runs. Input decks are stored in a version-controlled repository with run logs."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum linear elastic model with frictional contact is appropriate for monotonic quasi-static loading to yield; supported by literature and validated against experiment.",
      "rationale": "The pedicle screw and rod are modeled as Ti-6Al-4V linear elastic solids with frictional contact at the screw-rod interface (mu = 0.25). For monotonic quasi-static loading up to yield under ASTM F1717 conditions, this model form captures the dominant load-transfer mechanics. Post-yield plasticity is not required for the three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm). Model form uncertainty is partially characterized by the multi-code ensemble spread (CV < 3% across three codes)."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from certified material test reports for each lot; geometric inputs from CMM measurements; contact friction from dedicated friction characterization tests.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus (E = 114 ± 3 GPa) and yield strength sourced from lot-specific material test reports conforming to ASTM F136. Screw and rod geometry verified against CMM measurements to within ±0.02 mm. Interface friction coefficient (mu = 0.25 ± 0.04) derived from dedicated pin-on-flat tribology tests. Input uncertainty is propagated through a Monte Carlo analysis (N=500 runs) as reported in the UQ section of the credibility report; a screening sensitivity study described in that report verbally identifies elastic modulus and friction coefficient as the two largest contributors to stiffness variance, though the structured sensitivity analysis record has not been separately encoded in this package."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N >= 10 specimens from production lots; two independent laboratories; lot traceability documented.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested: six at Laboratory A (FDA CDRH) and five at Laboratory B (DePuy Synthes). All specimens drawn from the same production lot with full material and dimensional traceability. Inter-laboratory reproducibility assessed; coefficient of variation for stiffness across labs is 4.1%, within acceptable bounds."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions replicate COU loading environment; multiple load levels or conditions tested where clinically relevant variation exists.",
      "rationale": "Testing performed strictly per ASTM F1717 at a single load level (monotonic compression-bending to 40 mm displacement at 25 mm/min crosshead speed, ambient laboratory conditions). Only one test condition was evaluated; no variation in load rate, temperature, or simulated physiological fluid was included. This limitation is acknowledged; the factor achieves Gradation 2 rather than the required Gradation 3, representing the single below-requirement factor in this assessment."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA model inputs (geometry, material, boundary conditions) demonstrably equivalent to as-tested specimen parameters within measurement uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "FEA geometry reconstructed from CMM measurements of the actual tested specimens. Material properties assigned from lot-specific certificates matching the tested hardware. Boundary conditions replicate the ASTM F1717 fixture geometry (rigid superior block, pinned inferior block, 25 mm offset). Equivalency confirmed by overlay of FEA and experimental load-displacement curves in the linear elastic regime."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval < 1.96 for all three QoIs; mean absolute percent error < 10%.",
      "rationale": "All three QoIs satisfy both acceptance criteria: stiffness (MAPE 4.2%, E/uval 0.87), yield force (MAPE 6.8%, E/uval 1.42), force at 40 mm (MAPE 7.3%, E/uval 1.61). The validation uncertainty (uval) incorporates experimental measurement uncertainty, inter-laboratory variability, and numerical uncertainty estimated from the mesh convergence study."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are directly used in the regulatory submission decision and are mechanistically linked to clinical failure modes.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness relates to load sharing with the spine and adjacent-level effects. Yield force is the primary safety-relevant QoI tied to implant fracture risk. Force at 40 mm displacement characterizes post-yield energy absorption. All three QoIs are explicitly referenced in the 510(k) submission acceptance criteria and are standard ASTM F1717 reported quantities."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activity uses the same model, same loading scenario, and same QoIs as the COU; any differences are bounded and justified.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity is co-extensive with the COU: the same FEA model ensemble, the same ASTM F1717 loading scenario, the same three QoIs, and the same non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw geometry. The only acknowledged gap is the single test condition (addressed under Test conditions factor). No extrapolation beyond the validated domain is claimed in the submission."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/cou1-noncannulated-decision-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 credibility factors meet or exceed required levels for a Model Risk Level 3, Medium assurance assessment. The single below-requirement factor (Test conditions, achieved Gradation 2 vs. required Gradation 3) is accepted on the basis that ASTM F1717 specifies a single standardized test condition and no clinically meaningful variation in load rate or environment has been demonstrated to alter the QoIs beyond the established acceptance bounds. Uncertainty quantification via Monte Carlo propagation (N=500) confirms that all three QoIs satisfy E/uval < 1.96. The overall credibility evidence is judged sufficient to support the regulatory submission decision.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
